    <div class="text_separator"></div>
    <div class="text_separator"></div>
    <div class="ws-article-title">
		The Four Phases of Clinical Drug Trials
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-highlight">
		The information below quotes and refers to this site
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<b>What Are Clinical Trials and Studies?</b>
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
		National Institute on Aging (nih.gov)
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<a href="https://www.nia.nih.gov/health/what-are-clinical-trials-and-studies" target="_blank">
			What Are Clinical Trials and Studies? | National Institute on Aging (nih.gov)
	    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
			www.nia.nih.gov/health/what-are-clinical-trials-and-studies
		</a>
    	<div class="text_separator"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Clinical trials are carried out in phases* 
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		Clinical trials advance through four phases to test a drug, find the appropriate dosage, and look for side effects. 
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		If, after the first three phases, researchers find a drug to be safe and effective, the FDA approves it for clinical use and continues to monitor its effects.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Phase I trial emphasises SAFETY.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		Tests the experimental drug on a small group of often healthy people to judge If it’s SAFE, IDENTIFY SIDE EFFECTS, and to find the CORRECT DRUG DOSAGE.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		Typically less than 100 people.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Phase II trial empathises EFFECTIVENESS. 
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		Tests the experimental drug to obtain preliminary data on whether the drug WORKS in people who have a certain disease or condition. Also continue to study SAFETY, including SHORT-TERM SIDE EFFECTS. 
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		Typically 100 to 300 people. 
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		This phase can last several YEARS
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Phase III trial emphasises EFFECTIVENES & SAFETY especially monitoring SIDE EFFECTS.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		Tests the experimental drug studying different populations and different dosages, using the drug in combination with other drugs and continues the monitoring of side effects.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		Typically 100s to 3000 people / as many as needed or able to enrol.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		New Drug Application (NDA)
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		An application submitted by the manufacturer of a drug to the FDA, after the clinical trial has been completed, for a license to market the drug for a specified indication.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		If the FDA agrees that the Phase III trial results are positive, it will APPROVE the experimental drug.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Phase IV trial emphasises EFFECTIVENESS & SAFETY especially monitoring SIDE EFFECTS for the drug after the FDA approves its use.
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		When the new drug has being approved and marketed, Phase IV studies monitor its effectiveness in the general population and collect information about any adverse effects associated with its widespread use. Sometimes, the side effects of a drug may not become clear until more people have taken it over a longer period of time.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		Typically 1000s of people in large, diverse populations.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<i>* Before the <a href="https://www.fda.gov/" target="_blank">U.S. Food and Drug Administration</a> (FDA) approves a clinical trial to begin, scientists perform laboratory tests and studies in animals to test a potential therapy’s safety and efficacy. If these studies show favorable results, the FDA gives approval for the intervention to be tested in humans.</i>
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-subtitle">
		Finding Clinical Trial Information - ClinicalTrials.gov database
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-black">
		The ClinicalTrials.gov database holds information about privately and publicly funded clinical studies conducted around the world. It is provided by the U.S. National Library of Medicine.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		The ClinicalTrials.gov Identifier is a useful trial reference code e.g. NCT05096260. Enter the code in the “Other terms” search field on the Home Screen.
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<a href="https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/home" target="_blank">
			Home - ClinicalTrials.gov 
			<div class="text_separator"></div>
			https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/home 
		</a>
    </div>
    <div class="ws-article-arial-green">
	    <div class="ws-article-arial-green-comment">
			Our Comment
	    </div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		Critics argue that clinical drug trials can be deliberately designed to lead to data outcomes that falsely credit or discredit the hypothetical usefulness of a specific drug as a specific treatment. 
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		<div class="text_separator"></div>
		As such, trial design should be carefully analysed to check the trial is not biased and that it has been implemented with integrity including the management of data. 
    </div>
	<div class="text_separator"></div>
	<div class="text_separator"></div>
	<div class="text_separator"></div>
	<div class="text_separator"></div>
</div>
